@startuml c4-jotp-10a-concurrency-model
title JOTP - Concurrency Model: Virtual Threads vs Traditional

rectangle "Traditional Thread Pool Model" as Traditional {
    rectangle "OS Threads\n(Platform Threads)" as OSThreads {
        object "T1 (Block I/O)" as T1 {
          note
            Blocked waiting
            Wastes resources
            ~1MB per thread
          end note
        }
        object "T2 (Compute)" as T2 {
          note
            Running task
            CPU active
          end note
        }
        object "T3 (Idle)" as T3 {
          note
            Waiting for work
            Consumes memory
          end note
        }
    }
}

rectangle "JOTP Virtual Thread Model (Java 21+)" as Virtual {
    rectangle "Virtual Threads\n(Millions possible)" as VThreads {
        object "V1 (Block I/O)" as V1 {
          note
            Blocked - unmounts carrier
            Carrier serves V2
            ~1-5KB per thread
          end note
        }
        object "V2 (Compute)" as V2 {
          note
            Running on carrier
            Interleaved execution
          end note
        }
        object "V3 (Idle)" as V3 {
          note
            Parked - minimal memory
            Wakes on unpark()
          end note
        }
        object "V4 (Message Wait)" as V4 {
          note
            Blocked on mailbox.take()
            Unmounts carrier
          end note
        }
        object "V5 (Timer)" as V5 {
          note
            Scheduled delivery
            Lightweight delay
          end note
        }
    }

    rectangle "Carrier Threads\n(~1 per CPU core)" as Carriers {
        object "Carrier 1" as C1 {
          note
            Mounts V2 (compute)
            Unmounts V1 (blocked)
          end note
        }
        object "Carrier 2" as C2 {
          note
            Mounts V3 (woken)
            Unmounts V4 (blocked)
          end note
        }
    }
}

Traditional -[hidden]-> Virtual

C1 -down-> V2: mount V2 (context switch cheap)
V1 .down.> Carriers: unmounts when blocked

C2 -down-> V3: mount V3 (was parked)
V4 .down.> Carriers: unmounts when blocked

note bottom of Virtual
  Benefits:
  - 100k+ processes feasible (vs 10k with platform threads)
  - Cheap context switches (no syscall cost)
  - Blocking I/O doesn't block carrier threads
  - Better CPU utilization
  - Simpler concurrency code
end note

note bottom of Traditional
  Limitations:
  - Each thread ~1MB memory
  - Context switches expensive (kernel mode switch)
  - Blocking I/O blocks entire thread
  - ~10k limit before thread-per-request fails
  - More complex pooling code
end note

@enduml
